.TH "TRACEE\-CONFIG" "1" "2026/05" "" "Tracee Config Flag Manual"
.SS NAME
tracee \f[B]\-\-config\f[R] \- Define global configuration options for
tracee
.SS SYNOPSIS
tracee \f[B]\-\-config\f[R] <file>
.SS DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\-\-config\f[R] flag allows you to specify global configuration
options for Tracee by providing a configuration file.
.PP
The configuration file supports structured (nested) YAML under each
top\-level key, or a list of CLI\-style flag strings under that same
key.
Dotted keys at the root of the file (for example
\f[CR]server.http\-address\f[R]) are not loaded; each subsystem must
appear as its own top\-level key (\f[CR]server\f[R], \f[CR]output\f[R],
\f[CR]logging\f[R], and so on).
.SS FILE FORMAT
The configuration file supports multiple formats:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]YAML\f[R]: Recommended format with clear hierarchy and comments
support
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]JSON\f[R]: Standard JSON format for programmatic generation
.SS USAGE
To use the \f[B]\-\-config\f[R] flag, you need to provide the path to
the configuration file:
.IP
.EX
tracee \-\-config /path/to/tracee\-config.yaml
.EE
.SS EXAMPLES
.SS Nested (Structured) Format
Example configuration file using nested YAML structure:
.IP
.EX
output\f[B]:\f[R]
  destinations\f[B]:\f[R]
    \f[B]\-\f[R] name\f[B]:\f[R] stdout_destination
      type\f[B]:\f[R] file
      format\f[B]:\f[R] json
      path\f[B]:\f[R] stdout

logging\f[B]:\f[R]
  level\f[B]:\f[R] info

enrichment\f[B]:\f[R]
  container\f[B]:\f[R]
    enabled\f[B]:\f[R] true

buffers\f[B]:\f[R]
  kernel\f[B]:\f[R]
    events\f[B]:\f[R] 2048
    artifacts\f[B]:\f[R] 1024
  pipeline\f[B]:\f[R] 10000

server\f[B]:\f[R]
  http\-address\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]:3366\[dq]
  metrics\f[B]:\f[R] true
  healthz\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.SS CLI\-Style (List) Format
The same configuration using CLI\-style lists under each top\-level key.
Each entry is one flag string, like on the command line.
.IP
.EX
output\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] destinations.stdout_destination.type=file
  \f[B]\-\f[R] destinations.stdout_destination.format=json
  \f[B]\-\f[R] destinations.stdout_destination.path=stdout

logging\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] level=info

enrichment\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] container

buffers\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] kernel.events=2048
  \f[B]\-\f[R] kernel.artifacts=1024
  \f[B]\-\f[R] pipeline=10000

server\f[B]:\f[R]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] \[dq]http\-address=:3366\[dq]
  \f[B]\-\f[R] metrics
  \f[B]\-\f[R] healthz
.EE
.PP
For a complete example configuration file with all available options,
see:
https://github.com/aquasecurity/tracee/blob/main/examples/config/global_config.yaml
.SS NOTES
The following options are \f[B]not\f[R] supported in the configuration
file and must be provided exclusively via the CLI:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]\-\-config\f[R]: Path to the config file itself.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]\-\-policy\f[R]: Policy file or directory paths.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]\-\-scope\f[R]: Scope filters.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]\-\-events\f[R]: Event filters.
.PP
Policies can also be supplied through Kubernetes CRDs when running in a
cluster.
